# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: augusta-georgia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:augusta-georgia/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:augusta-georgia/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:augusta-georgia/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:augusta-georgia/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:augusta-georgia/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:augusta-georgia/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:augusta-georgia/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:augusta-georgia/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:augusta-georgia/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:augusta-georgia/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:augusta-georgia/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:augusta-georgia/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Census Bureau, Augusta had a 2020 population of 202,071 and a 2025 estimated population of 201,999, not counting the independent cities of Blythe and Hephzibah located within the boundaries of Augusta-Richmond County.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] It is the 124th most populous city in the United States and the 92nd-largest metropolitan area.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The process of consolidation between the city of Augusta and Richmond County began with a 1995 referendum in the two jurisdictions.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The merger was completed on July 1, 1996, but it excluded the municipalities of Blythe and Hephzibah.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta is the principal city of the Augusta metropolitan area.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In 2020 the metro area had a population of 611,000, making it the second-largest in the state (after Atlanta) and the ninth most populous urban center in the Deep South.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta was established in 1736 and is named in honor of Princess Augusta of Saxe-Gotha (1719–1772), the bride of Frederick, Prince of Wales and the mother of the British monarch George III.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] During the American Civil War, Augusta housed the principal Confederate Powderworks.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta's warm climate made it a major resort town of the Eastern United States in the early and mid-20th century.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Internationally, Augusta is best known for hosting the Masters golf tournament each spring.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Masters brings over 200,000 visitors from around the world to the Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta lies approximately two hours away from downtown Atlanta by car via I-20.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The city is home to Fort Gordon, a major U.S.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Army base formerly known as Fort Eisenhower.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In 2016, it was announced that the new National Cyber Security Headquarters would be based in Augusta.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In 1735, two years after James Oglethorpe founded Savannah, he sent a detachment of troops to explore the upper Savannah River.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] He gave them an order to build a fort at the head of the navigable part of the river.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The expedition was led by Noble Jones, who the following year created a settlement as a first line of defense for coastal areas against potential Spanish or French invasion from the interior.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Oglethorpe named the town in honor of Princess Augusta, the mother of King George III and the wife of Frederick, Prince of Wales.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Oglethorpe visited Augusta in September 1739 on his return to Savannah from a perilous visit to Coweta Town, near present-day Phenix City, Alabama.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] There, he had met with a convention of 7,000 Native American warriors and concluded a peace treaty with them in their territories in northern and western Georgia.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] During the American Revolutionary War, the Siege of Augusta resulted in the retaking the city from the British by the Americans.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta was the second state capital of Georgia from 1785 until 1795.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta developed rapidly as a market town as the Black Belt in the Piedmont was developed for cotton cultivation.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Invention of the cotton gin made processing of short-staple cotton profitable, and this type of cotton was well-suited to the upland areas.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Cotton plantations were worked by slave labor, with hundreds of thousands of slaves shipped from the Upper South to the Deep South in the domestic slave trade.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Many of the slaves were brought from the Lowcountry, where their Gullah culture had developed on the large Sea Island cotton and rice plantations.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] During the American Civil War, Augusta was home to many war industries, including the main facilities of the vast Confederate Powderworks.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] After the war, Augusta had a booming textile industry leading to the construction of many mills along the Augusta Canal to include Enterprise Mill, Sibley Mill, and King Mill.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The devastating Augusta fire of 1916 damaged 25 blocks of the city's downtown and wiped out many buildings of historical significance, some dating back to the 18th century.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta was a major center of economic activity during Reconstruction and thereafter.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In the mid-20th century, it was a site of civil rights demonstrations.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In 1970, Charles Oatman, a mentally disabled teenager, was killed by his cellmates in an Augusta jail.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] A protest against his death broke out into a riot involving some 500 people; during the unrest, six Black men were killed by police, each found to have been shot in the back.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The noted singer and entertainer James Brown, a native of Augusta, was called in to help quell lingering tensions, which he succeeded in doing.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In 1993, an area known as Hyde Park in Augusta was investigated by the EPA for contamination.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Air, groundwater, and soil were all believed to be contaminated, and people living in the area were hoping for government assistance to move away from Hyde Park.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Two of five neighborhoods in Hyde Park appeared to have arsenic, chromium, and dioxin, while all five were found to have PCBs and lead.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] However, residents were told it was not a risk to their health unless they somehow ingested it on a regular basis.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] At the time the article was written, the citizens still questioned why the EPA and ATSDR (Agency for Toxic Disease Registry) did not consider these chemicals as a threat to them.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Hyde Park also has higher rates of certain illnesses (such as cancer, infections, rashes) than the average in America, and the citizens question why that is not considered.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta is located along the Georgia/South Carolina border, about 150 mi (240 km) east of Atlanta and 74 mi (119 km) west of Columbia.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] According to the United States Census Bureau, the Augusta–Richmond County balance has a total area of 306.5 sq mi (793.8 km2), of which 302.1 sq mi (782.4 km2) is land and 4.3 sq mi (11.1 km2) (1.42%) is water.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta is located about halfway up the Savannah River on the fall line, which creates a number of small falls on the river.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The city marks the end of a navigable waterway for the river and the entry to the Georgia Piedmont area.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Clarks Hill Dam is built on the fall line near Augusta, forming Clarks Hill Lake.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Farther downstream, near the border of Columbia County, is the Stevens Creek Dam, which generates hydroelectric power.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Even farther downstream is the Augusta Diversion Dam, which marks the beginning of the Augusta Canal and channels Savannah River waters into the canal.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] As with the rest of the state, Augusta has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*), with short, mild winters, very hot, humid summers, and a wide diurnal temperature variation throughout much of the year, despite its low elevation and humidity.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The monthly daily average temperature ranges from 45.4 °F (7.4 °C) in January to 81.6 °F (27.6 °C) in July; there are 53 nights with the low reaching the freezing mark, 82 days reaching or exceeding 90 °F (32 °C), and 5.5 days reaching 100 °F (38 °C) annually.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Snowfall is not nearly as common as in Atlanta, due largely to Augusta's elevation, with downtown Augusta being about 900 ft (270 m) lower than downtown Atlanta.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The heaviest recorded snowfall was in February 1973 with 14.0 inches (36 cm) Freezing rain is also a threat in wintertime.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] At the 2020 United States census, there were 202,081 people, 66,838 households, and 41,517 families residing in the city.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] During the 2010 U.S. census, the city's population was 195,844, up from 195,182 at the 2000 United States census.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In 2000, the city's racial and ethnic composition was 43.72% non-Hispanic white, 49.96% African American, 0.25% Native American, 1.50% Asian, 0.11% Pacific Islander, 0.18% some other race, 1.48% multiracial, and 2.79% Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] By the 2020 census, its racial and ethnic makeup was 35.52% non-Hispanic white, 55.19% African American, 0.24% Asian, 1.93% Asian, 0.19% Pacific Islander, 0.44% some other race, 3.91% multiracial, and 5.58% Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] This reflected nationwide trends of greater diversification since the beginning of the 21st century.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta is a regional center of medicine, biotechnology, and cyber security.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta University, the state's only public health sciences graduate university, employs over 7,000 people.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Along with Piedmont Augusta, the Medical District of Augusta employs over 25,000 people and has an economic impact of over $1.8 billion.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The city's three largest employers are Augusta University, the Savannah River Site (a Department of Energy nuclear facility) and the U.S.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Army Cyber Center of Excellence at Fort Gordon, which oversees training for Cyber, Signal Corps, and Electronic Warfare.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] With the establishment of the Georgia Cyber Center in Downtown Augusta, the Augusta metro region has become a hub for cyber security based companies looking to locate to the area in part as well to the establishment of the U.S.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Army Cyber Command relocating to Fort Gordon from Fort Meade.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta plays host to TechNet on a yearly basis which brings in various military, government, and private sector leaders to the area to showcase new cyber related products as well as discussions on cyber based collaboration efforts between the public and private sectors.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] As of February 2025, the metro area unemployment rate is 4.5%, slightly above the national average.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] There are 10 historic districts throughout the city of Augusta.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The most prominent, Augusta Downtown Historic District, encompasses most of downtown Augusta and its pre-Civil War area.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Augusta Downtown Historic District was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2004.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The tallest buildings in Augusta include the Lamar Building, River Place Condominiums, and Augusta University Building.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Augusta GreenJackets minor league baseball club, formerly located at Lake Olmstead Stadium in Augusta, now play at SRP Park along the Savannah River in North Augusta, South Carolina.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The team began to play in 1988 as the Augusta Pirates, affiliated with the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Later affiliated with the Boston Red Sox and the San Francisco Giants, the GreenJackets are now the Class A affiliate of the Atlanta Braves.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Augusta Rugby Football Club (ARFC) is a division 2 men's club competing in the Palmetto Rugby Union, part of the USA Rugby South Conference.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta has an all-female flat track roller derby team, the Soul City Sirens.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Founded in 2008, this league is all-volunteer, and skater owned.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Augusta Lynx were a minor-league professional ice hockey team based in Augusta, Georgia.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Lynx played their home games at the James Brown Arena from 1998 until 2008.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Lynx, who played in the ECHL, had affiliations with the Tampa Bay Lightning of the NHL and the Norfolk Admirals of the AHL.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Augusta RiverHawks were a professional minor league ice hockey team.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] They played in the Southern Professional Hockey League (SPHL) from 2010 to 2013.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] They played their home games at the James Brown Arena.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Augusta Stallions were a professional Arena football team founded in 1999.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] They were one of the 15 original teams to join the inaugural 2000 AF2 season.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] They started off in the American Conference, before switching to the Southeast Division in 2001, and then the Eastern Division in 2002.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta was also home to the former Augusta 706ers, a minor league professional basketball team in the American Basketball Association.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The team was founded in 2017 and stopped operations in December 2018 because of a lack of funds.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The team played all home games at the James Brown Arena.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta National Golf Club hosts the first major golf tournament of each year, The Masters.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Augusta Top Gun Series is a series of tournaments sanctioned by the Professional Disc Golf Association, held at various venues in Augusta, including Pendleton King Park and Lake Olmstead.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta hosted the Augusta Southern Nationals drag boat Race for 30 consecutive years.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Held on the Savannah River until 2016, the race was part of the Lucas Oil Drag Boat Racing Series.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta hosts one of the largest Ironman 70.3 competitions, which includes cycling around Augusta, running through Downtown Augusta, and swimming on the Savannah River.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] In 1995, citizens of Augusta and unincorporated parts of Richmond County voted to consolidate their city and county governments.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Citizens of Hephzibah and Blythe, also located in Richmond County, voted against joining in the merger, which took effect January 1, 1996.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The unified government consists of a mayor and ten commissioners.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Eight commissioners represent single-member districts, while two are elected at-large, each to represent a super district that encompasses half of Augusta-Richmond's population.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] A May 2024 referendum, giving the mayor full voting powers on the Augusta Commission, was approved by Augusta voters by 74%, with the mayor previously being allowed to vote only in the case of a tie on the commission.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The government is a Council–manager government, with the commission appointing a County Administrator to carry out ordinances and directives of the government.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Public K–12 schools in Augusta are managed by the Richmond County School System, which covers all of Richmond County.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The school system contains 36 elementary schools, 10 middle schools, and the following eight high schools: Glenn Hills, Butler, Westside, Hephzibah, T.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] (Academy of Richmond County), Lucy Craft Laney, and Cross Creek.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Johnson Health Science and Engineering Magnet High School, Davidson Fine Arts, and the Richmond County Technical Career Magnet School.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Once the schools merge into the new building, Glenn Hills Elementary will close.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The plan also calls for the closure of Jenkins-White Elementary School, the consolidation of John M.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Tutt Middle School with Langford Middle School into the new Langford-Tutt Middle School, and the closure of Murphey Middle School as its campus is redeveloped.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Richmond County System Board of education also plans to convert T.W.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Josey Comprehensive High School into a districtwide College and Career Academy for grades 9–12.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Private schools in Augusta include Aquinas High School, Curtis Baptist High School, and Westminster Schools of Augusta.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The daily newspaper in the city is *The Augusta Chronicle.* Television stations serving Augusta and its metropolitan market are WJBF, channel 6 (ABC, with The CW Plus on DT2); WRDW, channel 12, (CBS); WCES, channel 20 (PBS); WAGT, channel 26 (NBC); and WFXG, channel 54 (Fox).
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta's large medical community and patient population is served by the Medical Examiner (www.AugustaRx.com), a twice-monthly newspaper published since 2006.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Parts of Augusta are served by city transit service Augusta Public Transit (APT), but the main mode of transportation within the city is by car.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta is also served by a number of taxi companies.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The city has two airports: Augusta Regional Airport and Daniel Field.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Augusta Regional Airport is served by two passenger airlines, including Delta Connection, which offers service to Atlanta, and American Eagle, which offers service to Charlotte, Dallas-Ft.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The last Seaboard Coast Line (the successor to the Atlantic Coast Line) train was a Florence-Augusta section of the *Champion;* this section ended in 1970.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The last train to the city was the unnamed daily in-state Georgia Railroad train between Atlanta and Augusta.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] This latter train, unofficially called the *Georgia Cannonball*, ran as a mixed train, until May 6, 1983.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Most trains went to the Union Station at Barrett Square.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] The Southern Railway trains went to the Southern Railway depot at Fifth and Reynolds Street.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Today, freight service is handled by Norfolk Southern Railway's Georgia Division and Piedmont Division through their Augusta Yard and Nixon Yard located near the city.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Norfolk Southern Trains such as the NS 191 and 192 pass through Augusta's downtown as they "street run" at 5 mph (8 km/h) down 6th street.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] They also cross the old Trestle over the Savannah River entering and leaving South Carolina.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] CSX Transportation Atlanta Division and Florence Division Trains also serve the Augusta, Georgia, area from the CSX Augusta Yard near Gordon Highway southwest of the city.
[src:augusta-georgia/augusta-georgia] Law enforcement in Augusta is handled by the Richmond County Sheriff's Office.
